  <h2>Feline-Focused Veterinary Care in Lake in the Hills</h2>
  <p>
    Cats aren't small dogs — and they shouldn't be treated like them. At Healthy Paws Animal Hospital, we understand that cats have unique health needs, behavioral tendencies, and exam requirements that demand a different approach. As a practice <a href="/low-stress-vet-lake-in-the-hills-il/">dedicated to gentle, low-stress care</a>, we're especially committed to making veterinary visits less stressful for our feline patients — because we know that a calm cat leads to better exams, more accurate diagnoses, and healthier outcomes.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Cats Need Specialized Veterinary Attention</h2>
  <p>
    Cats are masters at hiding illness. In the wild, showing weakness means becoming prey — and that survival instinct is still hardwired into your house cat. By the time most cat owners notice something is wrong, the problem has often been developing for weeks or even months. That's why regular veterinary care with a team that knows what to look for in cats is so important.
  </p>
  <p>
    Common signs of illness that cat owners often miss include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Subtle weight changes — even a half-pound loss in a 10-pound cat is significant</li>
    <li>Slight changes in water intake or litter box habits</li>
    <li>Sleeping in different spots or withdrawing from family interaction</li>
    <li>Changes in grooming behavior — over-grooming or a dull, unkempt coat</li>
    <li>Bad breath, which often indicates <a href="/dental-care/">dental disease</a> — the most common health problem in cats over age 3</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Our Cat-Specific Exam Approach</h2>
  <p>
    Every feline exam at Healthy Paws is designed around how cats experience the world — not how dogs do. Here's what makes the difference:
  </p>

  <h3>A Low-Stress Environment for Cats</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Feliway pheromone diffusers</strong> in exam rooms create a calming environment that speaks directly to feline instincts</li>
    <li>Carriers are covered with a towel during the wait to reduce visual stimulation</li>
    <li>Your cat gets <strong>time to explore the exam room</strong> before we begin — many cats will come out of the carrier on their own terms when given the chance</li>
    <li>We examine cats on soft, non-slip surfaces — never cold metal tables</li>
    <li>Gentle, <strong>minimal-restraint handling</strong> replaces the "scruff and hold" approach that makes cats defensive</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Feline-Specific Diagnostics</h3>
  <p>
    Cats have different normal ranges for bloodwork values, different disease patterns, and different nutritional needs than dogs. Our team uses feline-specific reference ranges for <a href="/laboratory-diagnostics/">laboratory diagnostics</a> and stays current on the latest research in feline medicine. We know that a thyroid value that's "normal" for a dog may signal hyperthyroidism in a cat, and that kidney disease — the leading cause of death in senior cats — requires early detection through targeted screening.
  </p>

  <h2>Comprehensive Cat Care Services</h2>
  <p>
    Whether your cat is a kitten, an adult, or entering their senior years, we provide complete veterinary care tailored to their life stage.
  </p>

  <h3>Kitten Care</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Core <a href="/pet-vaccinations-lake-in-the-hills-il/">vaccinations</a> (FVRCP, rabies) on an age-appropriate schedule</li>
    <li>Feline leukemia testing and FeLV vaccination based on risk</li>
    <li>Parasite screening and prevention</li>
    <li><a href="/spay-neuter-lake-in-the-hills-il/">Spay or neuter</a> scheduling and pre-surgical consultation</li>
    <li><a href="/microchipping/">Microchipping</a> for permanent identification</li>
    <li>Nutrition guidance for healthy growth</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Adult Cat Wellness</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Annual <a href="/wellness-exams-lake-in-the-hills-il/">comprehensive wellness exams</a> with weight monitoring and dental assessment</li>
    <li>Vaccine boosters on a schedule tailored to your cat's lifestyle (indoor vs. outdoor)</li>
    <li><a href="/dental-care/">Professional dental cleanings</a> — dental disease affects over 70% of cats by age 3</li>
    <li><a href="/nutrition-counseling/">Nutrition counseling</a> to maintain healthy weight and prevent obesity-related conditions</li>
    <li><a href="/pet-allergy-treatment-lake-in-the-hills-il/">Allergy and skin care</a> for cats with dermatologic issues</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Senior Cat Care</h3>
  <p>
    Cats are considered seniors around age 10, and their health needs increase significantly from that point forward. Our <a href="/senior-pet-care-lake-in-the-hills-il/">senior cat wellness program</a> includes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Semi-annual exams</strong> to catch age-related changes early</li>
    <li>Comprehensive bloodwork and urinalysis screening for kidney disease, hyperthyroidism, and diabetes</li>
    <li>Blood pressure monitoring — hypertension is common in older cats and can damage organs silently</li>
    <li><a href="/pain-management/">Pain management</a> for arthritis — yes, cats get arthritis too, and they're very good at hiding it</li>
    <li>Cognitive health monitoring and quality-of-life assessments</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Indoor Cats Still Need Regular Vet Visits</h2>
  <p>
    One of the most common misconceptions we hear is that indoor cats don't need regular veterinary care. While indoor cats face fewer risks from trauma and infectious disease, they're still susceptible to:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Dental disease</li>
    <li>Obesity and diabetes</li>
    <li>Kidney and thyroid disease</li>
    <li>Urinary tract issues</li>
    <li>Cancer</li>
    <li>Parasites brought in on shoes and clothing</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Illinois law also requires all cats to be vaccinated against rabies, regardless of whether they go outside. Annual wellness exams are the single best way to catch problems early — when treatment is most effective and least expensive.
  </p>

  <h2>The Healthy Paws Feline Care Team</h2>
